n, drama, tragicomedy, and conflict of a society in transition—will be an invaluable resource for scholars in Middle Eastern studies, Jewish studies, and contemporary European history. The wealth of documentation, much of it previously unknown or unpublished, makes this a particularly useful book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aJews-Libya-History. 0aLibya-Ethnic relations. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aFellah, Rafello.1 aRoumani, Judith.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74016740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477304099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477304099/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK